{
  "texts": [
    "During the growth of the rice plant, these husks typically account for about 30% of the total weight of the rice kernels.",
    "Made up mainly of organic material 80% organic and 20% inorganic rice husks are transformed into (RHA) when burned.",
    "This transformation gives RHA strong pozzolanic properties [35], largely due to its fine particle size.",
    "RHA is classified as a Class F pozzolan, primarily because of its low calcium oxide (CaO) content, which is less than 10%.The Review Discover Civil Engineering (2024) 1:145 | https://doi.org/10.1007/s44290-024-00154-z process of converting rice husks into RHA not only repurposes this agricultural by-product but also significantly increases its value in the construction industry.",
    "RHA is further distinguished by its relatively large particle size, which contributes to a high surface area [3]."
  ]
}